Please see section 9.8 (R801, ‚Ä¶, R814) of the game manual - if you have a pneumatics system it must conform to these rules, and the Inspectors at competition will enforce it. Be sure to practice adjusting the Pressure Release Valve before competition so it‚Äôll look like you know what you‚Äôre doing. Please see R811 and its link to FIRST Robotics Competition Pneumatics Manual .

I note the black Clippard AVT-PP-35 tanks are labeled ‚ÄúDO NOT INSTALL TANK IN AN EXPOSED AREA. TO REDUCE RISK OF INJURY FROM TANK RUPTURE, MOUNT TANK SO THAT IS PROTECTED FROM IMPACT‚Äù which we don‚Äôt enforce, or even mention. At SFR a few years ago a black Clippard tank had one end sheared off in a collision, ( POP ) but it didn‚Äôt fragment.

Years ago the rules allowed off-board compressors,  but that‚Äôs long gone.

posts.name: Gus Michel II
posts.cooked:
Mr.R_2:

mounted our tank ‚Ä¶ in the C portion of the KOP chassis

+2 to this - both 2016 and 2018, the two most recent times I used pneumatics on an FRC robot.  Too many things broke in 2016, but the pneumatics kept going through competition season and a summer full of demos.  In 2018, pneumatics became more important for post-season events than in-season, and that post-season robot was certainly the most competitive robot 3946 ever fielded.  Both of these robots used a Bimba flatline 502 cylinder to drive an arm at short distances from the pivot - and given a choice, I‚Äôd go with a short stout cylinder near the pivot over a long one (like we used in 2012, 2013, and 2014) any time.  A bent shaft is a bad day, and long skinny shafts are way more likely to get bent.
